What is the most devastating virus to folded proteins?
The most devastating threat to protein folding isn't a "virus" in the biological sense (like the flu or COVID-19), but rather a "misfolded" protein that acts like a pathogen: the Prion.
While biological viruses hijack a cell to create more viruses, prions hijack the shape of other proteins. They are essentially the "zombies" of the molecular world.
The Mechanism of Destruction
Normal proteins must fold into precise three-dimensional shapes to function. Prions are versions of these proteins that have folded incorrectly into a stable, "infectious" form.
Template-Directed Refolding: When a prion (PrP^{Sc}) comes into contact with a healthy, normally folded protein (PrP^{C}), it forces the healthy protein to flip its shape and become a prion too.
Aggregation: These misfolded proteins are extremely stable and resistant to heat, radiation, and chemical disinfectants. They clump together to form amyloid plaques.
Cellular Death: In the brain, these clumps tear holes in the tissue, leading to a "spongiform" (sponge-like) appearance and rapid neurological decline.
Why They are More "Devastating" Than Viruses
No Genetic Material: Unlike viruses, prions contain no DNA or RNA. This makes them nearly impossible for the immune system to detect or "kill."
Extreme Resilience: You can't "kill" a prion with standard sterilization. They can survive being autoclaved at 121°C and remain infectious in soil for years.
100% Fatality: Diseases caused by prions, such as Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD) in humans or Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE) in cattle, currently have no cure and are invariably fatal.
Other "Protein Killers"
If you are looking for biological entities that specifically target protein structures, you might consider:
Proteolytic Enzymes: Certain venoms or bacterial secretions (like those from Vibrio vulnificus) produce proteases that literally shred protein chains, causing rapid tissue necrosis.
Heat Shock: Not a virus, but extreme thermal energy is the most common "killer" of protein folds, causing denaturation—the unfolding of the protein into a useless string of amino acids.
While prions aren't technically alive, their ability to "infect" the geometry of a fold makes them the ultimate predator of functional proteins.
